We study the chain-length dependence of the donor lifetime for the same fractions as studied in Fig. 2. The time-resolved fluorescence decays (Fig. 4a) show a clear decrease in donor lifetime with increasing chain length, indicating an increase in energy transfer efficiency, in line with the spectral observations in Fig. 2. We deconvolve the time-resolved fluorescence decay curves by fitting them to a series of exponential decays to obtain the excited state lifetime distributions, as shown in Fig. 4b. All fractions exhibit a rather broad lifetime distribution. We speculate that this is due to the internal remaining polydispersity index (PDI) within each fraction. To elucidate this point, we measure the width στ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
